The goal is to remove all occurrences of val in-place. 
We use a pointer k to track the position where the next valid element should be placed. 
As we scan the array, whenever we find an element not equal to val, we copy it to nums[k] and increment k. 
At the end, the first k elements contain all values except val, and k is returned.


Algorithm:

i tells where we are right now
k tells where to place the good element 

where good element is val != nums[i] 
i moves through the whole array from left to right.
k only moves when we find a value that is not equal to val.


Step 1: initialize k at 0
step 2: start looping from start of the array to length of the array -1 :
            if nums[i] i.e current value is not equal to the given input val then we move this to the front of the array to position k and increamet k
step 3: return k



code:
class Solution {
    public int removeElement(int[] nums, int val) {
        int k = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            if (nums[i] != val) {
                nums[k] = nums[i];
                k++;
            }
        }

        return k;
    }
}
